  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The CORDA dataset, hosted on Zenodo, demonstrates strong engagement with the research community, evidenced by its 723 views and 306 downloads. Authored by a diverse team from key institutions including the University of Turin, this dataset contributes significantly to ongoing research efforts in its field.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The CORDA dataset, released on Zenodo, represents a foundational research output that has garnered substantial community engagement, reflected in its 723 views and 306 downloads. Such metrics illustrate the dataset's accessibility and technical value, indicative of its relevance in ongoing studies and applications within its discipline.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This dataset has been developed by a collaborative team of authors including Marta Alesina, Carlo Alberto Barbano, and others, representing prestigious institutions such as ASL Roma and A. O. Ordine Mauriziano di Torino. This involvement underscores the collaborative nature of contemporary research and highlights the institutional backing that lends credibility to the dataset.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although there are currently no citations or public discussions on platforms such as Wikipedia or Reddit, the dataset has been noted for its proven downstream reuse. This indicates that the data has facilitated additional research efforts, reinforcing its value and applicability in the broader scientific community, while aligning with best practices for data sharing and utilization.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The absence of funding affiliations does not diminish the significance of the CORDA dataset; rather, it reflects a commitment to open data practices that enhance the visibility and utility of research outputs. The dataset's presence in a reputable repository like Zenodo illustrates an important step in promoting data accessibility and scientific stewardship within the field.</p>",
